        content: "Understanding why attacks occur helps organizations assess their risk:\n\n**Financial Extortion**:\n- Ransom DDoS: Pay or suffer continued attacks\n- Competitive attacks: Disrupt rival businesses\n- Market manipulation: Attack targets before trading on price impact\n\n**Hacktivism**:\n- Political protest through digital disruption\n- Targeting organizations perceived as unethical\n- Anonymous and similar groups\n- Often timed with real-world events\n\n**Nation-State Operations**:\n- Disrupting critical infrastructure\n- Cyber warfare component\n- Political pressure through technical means\n- Covering other intrusion activities\n\n**Gaming and Entertainment**:\n- Disrupting online gaming competitors\n- Attacking streaming services\n- 'Swatting' and harassment\n- Testing attack capabilities\n\n**Revenge and Vandalism**:\n- Disgruntled employees or customers\n- Personal grudges\n- Trolling and 'lulz'\n\n**Smokescreening**:\n- DDoS as distraction during data breaches\n- Covering tracks during intrusions\n- Testing incident response capabilities\n\n**Business Risk Assessment**:\n- What are you worth attacking?\n- Who might want to attack you?\n- What's the cost of downtime?\n- These factors determine appropriate defense investment",
        keyTakeaway: "Attack motivations range from profit to protest to personal vendetta—any organization with an online presence is a potential target, and understanding your risk profile guides defense investments."
